<article>
    <h1>CITIES UN&#xAD;DER SIEGE</h1>
    <h2>Med&#xAD;i&#xAD;cal waste is in&#xAD;un&#xAD;dat&#xAD;ing dump sites in Asia&#x2019;s big cities, some end&#xAD;ing up in lakes, rivers and even road&#xAD;sides. The num&#xAD;bers are stag&#xAD;ger&#xAD;ing but vi&#xAD;able so&#xAD;lu&#xAD;tions are few.&#xD;&#xA;In&#xAD;dia chok&#xAD;ing as waste treat&#xAD;ment fa&#xAD;cil&#xAD;i&#xAD;ties fall short</h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20210109/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2021-01-09"><time>2021-01-09</time></a>
        - <span>NEWS FOCUS ASIAN INSIDER</span>
        - <span role="byline">Ro&#xAD;hini Mo&#xAD;han&#xD;&#xA;In&#xAD;dia Cor&#xAD;re&#xAD;spon&#xAD;dent In Ban&#xAD;ga&#xAD;lore rmo&#xAD;han@sph.com.sg</span>
    </section>

    <p>Since Septem­ber 2019, Mr Sub­hash Chan­dran, 32, has been div­ing off Rushikonda Beach to clean up the seabed in the coastal city of Visakha­p­at­nam in Andhra Pradesh.</p>
    <p>That year, the scuba div­ing in­struc­tor and his friends re­moved over 21 tonnes of plas­tic in 61 fourhour-long dives.</p>
    <p>But last Novem­ber, when they did their first un­der­wa­ter clean-up dur­ing the pan­demic, they found a jumble of masks, gloves and empty medicine sa­chets.</p>
    <p>“Nor­mally we find a lot of plas­tic bot­tles and wrap­pers. Since the pan­demic, we found 1,500kg of mostly N95 masks, sur­gi­cal masks, tablet pack­ets and gloves. I con­sider the ocean my sec­ond home, but it is a Covid-19 dump yard to­day,” Mr Chan­dran said.</p>
    <p>Med­i­cal waste, al­ready grow­ing at 7 per cent an­nu­ally pre-pan­demic, has ex­ploded with the pro­fu­sion of plas­tic pro­tec­tive gear to bat­tle coro­n­avirus trans­mis­sion.</p>
    <p>The Cen­tral Pol­lu­tion Con­trol Board said In­dia has gen­er­ated 18,006 tonnes of bio­med­i­cal waste from June to Septem­ber last year.</p>
    <p>This in­cludes per­sonal pro­tec­tive equip­ment such as gloves, face masks, head cov­ers, plas­tic cov­er­alls and haz­mat suits, as well as sy­ringes and other items used by health­care providers and pa­tients.</p>
    <p>On av­er­age, In­dia gen­er­ated about 101 tonnes of Covid-19-re­lated bio­med­i­cal waste a day in June. This rose to 183 tonnes per day in Septem­ber.</p>
    <p>This is in ad­di­tion to 609 tonnes of reg­u­lar bio­med­i­cal waste gen­er­ated per day as of last June.</p>
    <p>Ex­perts say the rise in waste gen</p>
    <p>er­a­tion is di­rectly re­lated to the num­ber of cases.</p>
    <p>In­dia has recorded over 10.4 mil­lion Covid-19 cases.</p>
    <p>In re­sponse to the pan­demic, the En­vi­ron­ment Min­istry and pol­lu­tion con­trol de­part­ments pub­lished guide­lines such as us­ing dou­ble-layer bags for dis­posal, manda­tory la­belling of bags and con­tain­ers as “Covid-19 waste”, and sep­a­rate record-keep­ing of waste gen­er­ated from iso­la­tion wards.</p>
    <p>These are in ad­di­tion to ex­ist­ing rules for bio­med­i­cal man­age­ment from 2016, which man­date colour­coded seg­re­ga­tion of med­i­cal waste. Covid-19 waste is now sup­posed to go into yel­low bins.</p>
    <p>But waste man­age­ment ex­perts say proper seg­re­ga­tion and dis­posal have been se­ri­ously ne­glected.</p>
    <p>“Used masks must be dis­in­fected with sodium hypochlo­rite so­lu­tion, left for 72 hours, mu­ti­lated (cut or</p>
    <p>torn), cov­ered in a pa­per bag and then thrown in reg­u­lar bins,” said Ms Pinky Chan­dran, a mem­ber of cit­i­zen al­liance Hasiru Dala that pro­motes waste seg­re­ga­tion in Ban­ga­lore and works with the city au­thor­i­ties to help dis­pose of waste.</p>
    <p>“Some hos­pi­tals and com­mer­cial es­tab­lish­ments fol­low the rules some­what, but house­holds and clin­ics are quite lax.”</p>
    <p>While more In­di­ans are us­ing wash­able cloth masks, which “greatly re­duces the waste gen­er­ated”, she said each of Ban­ga­lore’s over 120 waste col­lec­tion cen­tres has been see­ing at least 300 masks daily.</p>
    <p>In­dia has 198 com­mon bio­med­i­cal waste treat­ment fa­cil­i­ties for treat­ing and dis­pos­ing of Covid-19 bio­med­i­cal waste, but these are prov­ing to be in­ad­e­quate.</p>
    <p>Tamil Nadu, for in­stance, has only eight com­mon bio­med­i­cal</p>
    <p>waste treat­ment fa­cil­i­ties, with a ca­pac­ity of 31 tonnes a day.</p>
    <p>The state, how­ever, gen­er­ated 47 tonnes of bio­med­i­cal waste a day, be­fore the pan­demic.</p>
    <p>In­dia’s most pop­u­lated state, Uttar Pradesh, gen­er­ated 247 tonnes of bio­med­i­cal waste per day in July al­though its treat­ment fa­cil­i­ties can treat only 10 tonnes a day.</p>
    <p>Ex­perts rec­om­mend more per­son­alised outreach for cre­at­ing aware­ness and more data col­lec­tion and track­ing of bio­med­i­cal waste.</p>
    <p>Mr Jai Prakash Choud­hary from Safai Sena, a col­lec­tive of 12,000 of Delhi’s waste pick­ers, said: “Since peo­ple throw out masks as they are, we have to touch and seg­re­gate them from other waste. It’s just God’s bless­ing that I haven’t been in­fected with the virus yet.”</p>

